rious cinematic reproductions of London by filmmakers coming to this megacity from abroad. As visitors, cosmopolitans, or even migrant filmmakers, their treatment of London’s zonal locations as both foreign and familiar is fascinating; their narratives and visualisations of London’s spatial and architectural uniqueness is given a sojourners’ touch; while other foreign filmmakers showcase and sometimes problematise London’s socio-cultural globality and locality as both British and a city open (and sometimes closed off) to the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCities and towns in motion pictures. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2021. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAki Kaurismäki.  aAlfonso Cuarón.  aBollywood.  aEmeric Pressburger.  aFilm Studies.  aGavrik Losey.  aHenrique Goldman.  aHindi cinema.  aNollywood.  aSaskia Sassen.  aUrban Studies.  acinematic topography.  acosmopolitanism.  adigital happening.  aglobal London.  aglobalisation.  amulticulturalism.  asuperdiversity.  avisitor filmmakers.1 aBanaji, Shakuntala, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunsdon, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDennison, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFan, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlanagan, Kevin M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuha, Malini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLack, Roland-François, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLópez Fuentes, Ana Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartín, Móni